logging: adding counter to differentiate initial results (#3651)When setting up alerts for differential logs data you might want to skip therninitial added records. counter can be used to identify if the added recordsrnare all records from initial query of if they are new records. For initialrnquery results that includes all records counter will be 0. For subsequentrnquery executions counter will be incremented by 1. When epoch changes, counterrnwill be reset back to 0.

Refactor logStatus and logger initialization (#2081)The initialization of a logger plugin was confusing. The 'init' step wasrnintroduced to allow a daemon to buffer status events before a logger pluginrnis determined by external/remote configuration. The buffered statuses couldrnthen be transferred via a medium other than Glog (the default). To determinernif Glog should continue to write statuses to the filesystem the 'init' methodrnreturned a Status.rnrnLogger plugins should now use a feature method override to select how statusrnlogs should be handled.

Revive the OS X kernel-based publishers (#2083)The OS X kernel subscribers have not been starting because they expect thernpublisher thread to run before they begin configuration. Due to some recentrnrefactors the publisher thread creation now occurs after configuration.rnrnThe subscriber logic to check for a valid kernel connection is still valid.rnrnThis commit has two additional side-effects:rn- The RocksDB plugin is modified to use 3 background merge threads.rn- The OS X kernel publisher syncing thread is now non-blocking.

Introduce within-query caching (#2077)This adds a new optimization feature that allows expensive tables to cacherntheir results between JOINs. Consider JOINing a list of open sockets, for eachrnprocess, then requesting to hash each process path. This query may hashrnthe same path multiple times.rnrnWithin-query caching allows the hash table to respond with the previousrnresult of the hash request as long as the requested computation was the resultrnof a single query. Subsequent queries will perform subsequent hashing.

Renamed crash_log table. Small fixes to parsing behavior (#2074)Renamed the crash_log table to crashes for future abstraction to otherrnoperating systems. Also fixed how the table was parsing the most recentrnstack trace and the registers.  Register values are now all parsed intornone column 'registers', which will be a space delimited string of thernform:rnrnregister:value register:value ... register:valuernrnin order to best allow for OS abstraction.

Add local_timezone and datetime (ISO) to time table (#2073)It is often helpful to know the local timezone of the machine. For this usernlocal_timezone, as the base timezone will use local or UTC depending on thern--utc flag. This will be default=UTC in osquery 1.8.0.rnrnThe datetime field is added to mimic ISO 8601, along with iso_8601.rnThe timestamp field remains as the time stamp used for logging (within osquery)rnand commonly outside of osquery. The goal for adding multiple representationsrnis to allow joining/augmenting of other tables.

The 'time' table will respond with the parsed time for thernconfiguration. If the timezone is not UTC then osquery is using localtime.rnrnThis configuration option will affect the 'unix_time' response in the 'time'rntable. Use mnenomics for process states on DarwinProcess states in `processes` table now use mnemonics instead of theninteger code. They follow closely to the states defined sys/proc.h,nwhich means processes with state as:nn  statevalue   meaning   mnemonicn -------- ------- --------------------------------- ----------n  SIDL 1   process being created by fork 'I'n  SRUN 2   currently runnable'R'n  SSLEEP   3   sleeping on an address'S'n  SSTOP4   process debugging or suspension   'T'n  SZOMB5   awaiting collection by parent 'Z'nnNote: The mnemonics here will not match up with what `ps` or `top`nreports.nn`ps` and `top` queries run state of all Mach Threads (by grabbing a Mach Task)nof a process, and then coalesces it to represent the process state.nnThis is no longer possible to do by non-Apple signed binaries,nas the only way to a Mach Task (and therefore list of Mach Threads)nis by calling `task_for_pid()`, which no longer works undernSystem Integrity Protection (SIP) introduced in OS X 10.11n

Add linux syslog virtual tableThis commit adds an event-based virtual table implementation fornquerying the linux syslog. It introduces an event publisher thatnattaches to a named pipe to ingest CSV formatted syslog forwarded fromnrsyslogd. An event subscriber/virtual table makes these log linesnavailable for queries. Currently, no additional processing is done onnthe input data besides parsing.nnUsing this table requires a properly configured rsyslogd. Documentationnfor this configuration is forthcoming in the wiki.n

[fix #1536] Schedule iteration pass-by-referenceThere was a bug in the `osquery::Schedule` container object such that,nwhen the iteration through the schedule occured, pack objects were beingnpassed by value (copied) instead of passed by reference. Thus, thendiscovery query would be executed, the object's cache would be updated,nand then the object would go out of scope and be destructed, thusnleaving the original object without ever having ran the discovery query.nThis caused discovery queries to thrash. Bad times.nnI added a new test so that we don't regress here as well as const'd anfew functions that should have been const in `osquery::Pack`.n

[fix #1390] query pack re-orgThis commit contains the features specified in #1390 as well as anrefactoring of the general osquery configuration code.nnThe API for the config plugins hasn't changed, although now there's an`genPack` method that config plugins can implement. If a plugin doesn'tnimplement `genPack`, then the map<string, string> format cannot be used.nThe default config plugin, the filesystem plugin, now implementsn`genPack`, so existing query packs code will continue to work as itnalways has.nnNow many other config plugins can implement custom pack handling fornwhat makes sense in their context. `genPacks` is not a pure virtual, sonit doesn't have to be implemented in your plugin if you don't want tonuse it. Also, more importantly, all config plugins can use the standardninline pack format if they want to use query packs. Which is awesome.nnFor more information, refer to #1390, the documentation and the doxygenncomments included with this pull requests, as well as the followingnexample config which is now supported, regardless of what config pluginnyou're using:nn```jsonn{n  options: {nenable_monitor: truen  },n  packs: {ncore_os_monitoring: {nversion: 1.4.5,ndiscovery: [n  select pid from processes where name like '%osqueryd%';n],nqueries: {n  kernel_modules: {n  query: SELECT name, size FROM kernel_modules;,n  interval: 600n  },n  system_controls: {n  query: SELECT * FROM system_controls;,n  interval: 600,n  snapshot: true,n  },n  usb_devices: {n  query: SELECT * FROM usb_devices;,n  interval: 600n  }n}n},nosquery_internal_info: {nversion: 1.4.5,ndiscovery: [n  select pid from processes where name like '%osqueryd%';n],nqueries: {n  info: {n  query: select i.*, p.resident_size, p.user_time, p.system_time, time.minutes as counter from osquery_info i, processes p, time where p.pid = i.pid;,n  interval: 60,n  snapshot: truen  },n  registry: {n  query: SELECT * FROM osquery_registry;,n  interval: 600,n  snapshot: truen  },n  schedule: {n  query: select name, interval, executions, output_size, wall_time, (user_time/executions) as avg_user_time, (system_time/executions) as avg_system_time, average_memory from osquery_schedule;,n  interval: 60,n  snapshot: truen  }n}n}n  }n}n```nnThe `osquery_packs` table was modified to remove the superfluousncolumns which could already have been found in `osquery_schedule`. Twonmore columns were added in their place, representing stats about pack'sndiscovery query execution history.nnNotably, the internal API for the `osquery::Config` class has changednrather dramatically as apart of the refactoring. We think this is annimprovement. While strictly adhering to the osquery config pluginninterface will have avoided any compatibility errors, advanced users maynnotice compilation errors if they access config data directly. Allninternal users of the config have obviously been updated. Yet anothernreason to merge your code into mainline; we update it for you when wenrefactor!n

Optimize event publisher database namespace lookups.Previously, event publishers used a canonicalized 'type' name for async callbacks.nThis type was used to lookup the publisher plugin in the registry as well as for backing store namespacing.nThe type is still used but subscribers, which made heavy used of the lookup, store the value locally.nThis prevents unneeded publisher plugin allocation when adding events.n

Allow ConfigParserPlugins to update the ConfigData.Previously, `ConfigParserPlugin`s could only maintain an internal derived object called `data_`.nThen parts of the code that knew to use the plugin's data would call `getParsedData` and provide the name of the plugin.nnParser plugins can now request a mutable version of the `ConfigData` using `::mutableConfigData`.nThis requires a lock on the `ConfigDataInstance` and must be provided to their mutable accessor.nnAcess to a mutable config enables parsers to make modifications to internal config structures like options and the query schedule.n

[Fix #1171, #1089] Add configurable max readsThere are 3 new options that control how files are read:n--read_max: controls the maximum size, in bytes, for file reads. If a file is larger than `read_max` the read will fail.n--read_user_max: similar to `read_max` but applies additional limitations to user-controlled files.n--read_user_links: a boolean control to enable/disable following symlinks for user-controlled files.nnImportant highlights:nIf files exceed the configured max, those reads will fail.nThe `read_max` will override `read_user_max` if it is set lower.nA default integer value of `0` will disable the limitations.nnThe default `read_max` is set to 50M and the default `read_user_max` is 10M.n

The information given constitutes only a small portion ofnthe information in the model specific register, but this tablenhas been designed so that more information may easily be added.nThe table requires osquery be run as the root, and that the msrnkernel module is loaded. Implement process related tables on FreeBSD.This implements the following tables on FreeBSD:nnprocess_envsnprocess_memory_mapnprocess_open_filesnprocess_open_socketsnprocessesnnAll the heavy lifting is done with libprocstat(3). All the tables follownthe same general principle. Use the common function, getProcesses() innprocstat.cpp, to get the processes and then generate the rows for eachnprocess returned. There is also a procstatCleanup() function commonlynused across all the tables.nnThe one thing I am not able to test is the process_open_sockets table onnan IPv6 machine.n

Major YARA refactor and enhancements1. Rename yara_matches to yara_events.nn2. Add support for Config::getParser().n- This returns a ConfigPluginRef, which is the ConfigParser for then  given key.n- Being able to get the parser is useful because then  YARAConfigParserPlugin uses it to store the compiled rules as ann  attribute.nn3. Finish rename and use ConfigParserPlugin.n- Finish the table rename to yara_events.n- Use the new ConfigParserPlugin interface to parse the YARAn  configuration. The file_paths and signatures are stored in then  ConfigParserPlugin named yara under the key yara. The rules aren  compiled and stored as a private attribute of the samen  ConfigParserPlugin object.nnHere is an example config using this new structure:nn{n  // Description of the YARA feature.n  yara: {nsignatures: {n  // Each key is an arbitrary group name to give the signatures listedn  sig_group_1: [ /Users/wxs/foo.sig, /Users/wxs//bar.sig ],n  sig_group_2: [ /Users/wxs/baz.sig ]n},nfile_paths: {n  // Each key is a key from file_pathsn  // The value is a list of signature groups to run when an event firesn  // These will be watched for and scanned when the event frameworkn  // fire off an event to yara_events tablen  system_binaries: [ sig_group_1 ],n  tmp: [ sig_group_1, sig_group_2 ]n}n  },nn  // Paths to watch for filesystem eventsn  file_paths: {nsystem_binaries: [ /usr/bin/%, /usr/sbin/% ],ntmp: [ /Users/wxs/tmp/%% ]n  }n}nn- Currently the signature file must be an absolute path.nn3. Move common YARA code to yara_utils.n- In preparation for the yara table (different from yara_events) I'mn  moving the common YARA code into a separate place which is sharedn  between the two tables.nn4. Add yara table.n- This allows you to do things like:nn```sqlnselect * from yara where path=/bin/ls and sigfile=/tmp/foo.sig;nselect * from yara where path=/bin/ls and sig_group=sig_group_1;n```nn- The latter will use the signature grouping from the config.nn5. Check for keys not existing.n

Implement YARA table.Currently only for OS X, will port to others soon.nnAlso need to add tests.nnRemove old comment and add loading message.nnImplement YARA table for Linux.nnUse mask properly.nnUse the various masks to specify the kinds of events we are interestednin. This removes the need to do the dirty DELETED check when the eventnfires.nnMake getYARAFiles return a const map.nnSwitch to LOG(WARNING) and emit error number.nnAdd vim .swp files to .gitignore.nnAdd yara_utils.(c|h).nnStart to condense common code between the Linux and Darwin YARA tablesninto a yara_utils.h. Right now it includes a function to compile rulesnand store the results back in the map, indexed by category. It also hasnthe callback used by YARA when a rule is processed. I can not move muchnmore than that for the row creation code because the structures used innthe event callback are slightly different.nnInclude a better error message.nnThe errors are still printed by the compiler callback, but this willnallow my future work to return a Status from the event initialization tonprint a useful message in summary.nnMake Subscriber init() return Status.nnEach EventSubscriber::init() now returns a Status. If the init() failsnfor any reason the EventSubscriber is still stored but the failure isntracked.nnEventSubscribers now have a state member, which represents the currentnstate of the subscriber. The current supported states are:nuninitialized, running, paused, failed. Currently the only meaningfulnones are running and failed, but I put paused in there as anforward-looking feature.nnSubscriptions now have a subscriber_name member. This is used innEventPublisherPlugin::fire() as a lookup to get the EventSubscriber andncheck the state. If the EventSubscriber is not running the event willnnot fire.nnOnly the EventSubscribers on OS X are using this. I'll do the Linuxnimplementation next.nnChase the init() changes to Linux.nnThis brings the Linux YARA table in line with the OS X one.nnRequire a EventSubscriberID when creating a subscription.nnNow that Subscriptions are tied to EventSubscribers you must create anSubscription with the name of the Subscriber it is for. This is becausenwhen the event fires the list of Subscriptions is walked and the name isnused to lookup the EventSubscriber and make sure it is in the runningnstate.nnFix various tests.nnSome tests would fire an event with only a Subscription, which is nonlonger a valid thing to do. For these tests an EventSubscription isncreated and registered in the EventFactory.nnWhen Subscriptions are created pass the name of the EventSubscriber tonthem. In some cases where no event is ever fired it is fine to pass anbogus name.nnFix inotify tests.nnMove a test down so the class is defined and make sure to create annEventSubscriber and use it properly.nnAdd support for yara to provision.sh.nnRight now this grabs yara 3.3.0 and applies the patch to fix min() and max(),nwhich is commit fc4696c8b725be1ac099d340359c8d550d116041 in the yara repo.nnThis has been tested under Ubuntu 14.04 only.nnRemove NOMINMAX.nnThis is no longer necessary after the patch was backported to 3.3.0.nnRevert Add support for yara to provision.sh.nnThis reverts commit a8bd371498c0979f070adeff23d05571882ac3f1.nnUse vendored YARA code in third-party.nnThis switches to using the YARA code contained in third-party, includingnthe patch to fix min/max macros.nnFix mismerge.nnRemove unused function after merge.nnWell, soon to be unused as soon as I fix up the Linux YARA table. ;)nnChase config changes.nnMake the Linux YARA table use ConfigDataInstance along with files() andnyaraFiles().n

Updated as per your notesA couple of things to noternrnThe script still makes the assumption of having a config in /etc/osquery/osquery.conf however it now checks to see if there is the default example config in /usr/share/osquery/osquery.example.conf and alerts the user that it's using the default. rnrnTo prevent having the pidfile being set in two different locations, it would be nice if the osqueryd application settings could be stored with the standard key=value approach. This would allow the init script to source the config at runtime. The downside however would that the init script still makes the assumption that the location of osquery.conf is standardized. rnrnI'm not really sure why the pidfile needs to go in the osquery directory anyway, considering most pidfiles for daemons like this typically exists in /var/run/$program.pid which actually would be a nicer default as it removes the requirement of having the folder there in /var. I'd prefer to not keep osquery in /var anyway. rnrnsame goes for the lockfile. Typically you'd never bother with this setting and you'd keep it in /var/lock/subsys/$progname

Force git to return something if tags aren't foundIf there are no tags in the current repository, this command will fail leaving the OSQUERY_BUILD_VERSION blank, and therefore breaking the package building process (and presumably other things too) due to the empty version flag.  By adding the flag --always, this forces git to fallback to a commit id instead of returning nothing.

Of course, you could perhapsndenial of service osqueryd this way, but that would require rootnfilesystem access (assuming that the last version of osqueryd wasnran as root). Thoughts?n

Merge pull request #94 from facebook/results_serializer_perfFix performance issue with the disk serializer

Fix performance issue with the disk serializerThis is the issue noted in #76. Keeping all historical results ofnqueries in the HistoricalQueryResults struct makes serializing andndeserializing those structs very, very slow as time goes on. By onlynstoring the last execution of the query, we keep the performancenconstant, but we kill the feature where osquery can rebuild timelinesnwithout accessing logs. After talking it over, we decided that thisnisn't actually that big of a deal because, if you really wanted tonrebuild the old data, you should be able to process the logs, similarlynto bin log replication in MySQL.n
Close #79The leak is a FP. Ran it through some other memory analysis tools.nValgrind has historically has a hard time sorting out leaks vs ARC.n
